Is AI taking away my job? Insights over my second cup
The question everyone seems to be asking: Is AI taking away jobs? More specifically, is it coming for my job?
I'm adding my voice to the mix—not just with an opinion, but with a fresh-off-the-oven experience.
While working on the logo for my new newsletter The Second Cup, I decided to give AI tools a try. I fed them prompts, described the feel I wanted, and got some options that looked decent to my untrained, design-agnostic eye. Then I ran it by my talented graphic designer niece, Samhitha Chitturi, who has a degree in Art Direction and New Narratives.
As expected, she had an allergic reaction. 😅
Not because she detested AI tools, but because she knew what "good" looks like and was irked at me settling for something lesser.
After asking me questions that made me think deeper about the newsletter itself—its target audience, its purpose—she did something that seemed almost too simple. She asked me to write the newsletter name in my handwriting a few different times, in a few different ways.
She started with those pieces of paper and turned them into the logo. Simple, yet deeply meaningful. My own handwriting became the authenticity of voice I'm striving for. The colors are warm, earthy, and social-media friendly (she explained all this to me, of course).
What I learned:
Nobody—not even AI—can take away your craft and skills. But there's a crucial difference between having skills and knowing how to leverage them.

What I learned:
Nobody—not even AI—can take away your craft and skills. But there's a crucial difference between having skills and knowing how to leverage them.
Samhitha can make AI work for her because she knows how to squeeze the right juice from it. The difference between what AI generates for me versus what it generates for her is night and day. She has the expertise to set the right context, provide the right prompts, and validate using the right benchmarks.
AI tools certainly help many get a head start without relying on specialized skills. But don't let that trick you into thinking you're suddenly a "know it all" who doesn't need those specialized skills anymore. There's a difference between a quick prototype and quality work—whether that's code, design, or anything else.
Here's the shift: Don't treat AI as a deterrent or threat. Treat it as your assistant. Use it to force-multiply your existing skills so you can work faster and cheaper, giving you more time for what actually matters—life itself.
#AI #Design #Productivity #FutureOfWork

“What do you do?” — And Why That Question Can Wreck You If You’re Not Careful

We often think of “So, what do you do?” as a harmless icebreaker. But what if I told you this seemingly innocent question can quietly shape — or derail — the most important decisions in your life and career?
We often think our job is who we are — until life proves otherwise. In this piece, I share the moment I realized how fragile that illusion was, and the tools I wish I’d had to stay grounded in my true self.

💡 Lesson in a Line
Don’t let your job define your identity. You are a whole human as-is — and you are enough.
One question has quietly wrecked more midlife careers than burnout or bad bosses. It seems innocent enough — ‘So, what do you do?’ But for high achievers, that question can become a trap.

📖 Real Story
When Work Became My Whole World
Growing up in a traditional Indian household, academics were everything. Academic success wasn’t just encouraged—it was expected. Education was our golden ticket, and a “good job” was the price of a better life.
So, like many of us, I followed the script:
🎓 Undergrad in India. Master’s in the U.S. A stable job.
In the early years, all my energy went into building a foundation—figuring out visas, proving myself, staying financially secure. I gave 110% to work, because it felt like the right thing to do. The responsible thing.
And to be honest, it felt good.
🏆 Recognition came. Promotions followed. It was validating—almost addictive.
It felt like I was winning.
But slowly, everything else started to fade.
Our weekday gym and racquetball games? First, they moved to weekends. Then they stopped altogether.
Hobbies and other favorites? Pushed aside.
Weekends became about catching up on life and resting just enough and getting organized for another intense workweek.
Bit by bit, I stopped making space for myself.
Work didn’t just come first—it became everything.
And somewhere in that cycle of “achievement,” I lost touch with the parts of me that weren’t tied to a job title or performance review.
Then came a major life change: we packed our bags and moved back to India. I left my thriving career to focus on settling the family and spending time with our kids — a luxury I’d long craved after years of rushing between daycares and meetings.

Then came a major life change: we packed our bags and moved back to India. I left my thriving career to focus on settling the family and spending time with our kids — a luxury I’d long craved after years of rushing between daycares and meetings.
And yet, at my very first social gathering back in India, when someone casually asked me, “So, what do you do?” — I froze.
No job title. No shiny brand. Just... me.
And that felt hollow.
I became insecure. Within a month, I jumped into a startup. I didn’t give myself enough time to work through the details because I couldn’t bear the discomfort of not being someone. It wasn’t the wrong move — I led it with passion and learned a ton — but looking back, I know I wasn’t only driven by purpose. It was also fear. Fear of not being relevant. Of disappearing. 
🛠 Real-Life Guardrails — If You’re Not Careful, Work Will Take Everything
Here’s what I’ve learned the hard way — and what I’d do to protect my identity and joy:
Keep a hobby alive — even if it’s just 30 minutes a week. That badminton match, sketchpad, or playlist is a thread to who you are beyond the badge.
Block time for friends and family like you block time for meetings. Don’t just say “they matter.” Show it on your calendar. These relationships outlast any job title.
Pursue a passion project outside of work. It doesn’t have to make money. It just has to be yours.

Block time for friends and family like you block time for meetings. Don’t just say “they matter.” Show it on your calendar. These relationships outlast any job title.
Pursue a passion project outside of work. It doesn’t have to make money. It just has to be yours.
Don’t let recognition and promotions trick you into thinking work is the only thing you’re good at. That’s a lie that high performers often believe right before they break.
No job is worth losing yourself to.

🙋‍♀️ So, Who Am I?
Engineer, 3 Corporate Jobs (Sapient, Dow Jones, Amazon), Startup cofounder, Political volunteer. But those titles aren’t the whole story.
I’m also a mother of two boys. A wife. A sister. A daughter. A friend.
I wish I’d kept up badminton and cricket. These days, I love reading, writing, and music.
That’s who I am. Not just what I do.

🪞 Now Your Turn
💥 Challenge of the Week:
Ask yourself, “If I didn’t have a job title, how would I introduce myself?”
And second: “What would an ideal day look like if I had nothing to prove and money wasn’t a worry?
Write it down. Sit with it. Then ask: What’s stopping me from living even 10% of that now?
What part of your identity today still leans a bit too heavily on achievement?
Who do you want to be remembered as — beyond your LinkedIn bio?
If you gave yourself 90 days with no work obligations, how would you use that time?

🔁 What I’d Do Differently Now
I would’ve taken a true pause — not filled it out of panic.
I would’ve rediscovered myself, my interests, my people, still done the startup but after a bit more preparation and ground work done.
Today, when someone asks me what I do, I smile — and ask them, ‘At work or life?
The job is a means, not the identity.

🛡️ Zoom in to Zoom out. Repeat
Indra Nooyi, former CEO of PepsiCo, brilliantly articulated the power of 'zooming in and zooming out' for effective leadership. This isn’t a C-suite trick. It’s survival-level wisdom—for everyone. Details reveal what’s happening. Vision reveals what matters.
Whether you’re debugging code, leading a cross-functional initiative, or running a business unit, the same truth applies: You need to see the pixels and the picture. Most people favor one—but great leaders master both.
In this edition, I'll share the lessons I've learned about maintaining this balance, plus the practical tools and techniques that help me stay grounded in reality while constantly connecting the dots to something larger.
💡 Lesson in a Line
Don’t lose the forest for the trees—vision sets the direction; details shape the path.
📖 Real Stories
2 incidents come to mind about this topic. 
My First Hard Lesson in Zooming Out
Early in my career as a software engineer, I was assigned to build a complex dashboard for investment analysts at a major financial firm. I dove in headfirst—eager and excited to prove myself. I started by dissecting the data fields, designing SQL queries, tuning performance, optimizing database schemas, and experimenting with Oracle stored procedures and triggers. I was in my element—deep in the weeds, laser-focused on building a fast, scalable, and (what I believed to be) future-proof solution.

In our team standups, I clarified a few requirement details and kept the focus on building a technically elegant product. So, when demo day arrived, I was pumped—ready to show off what I’d built.
But the moment we presented to the users, the excitement evaporated. They stared at the dashboard and simply said, “These numbers don’t make sense.”
That was the gut-punch. I had completely missed the forest for the trees.
I hadn’t paused to ask the most important question: What business problem is this dashboard trying to solve? What story were the numbers meant to tell? I was so focused on the “how,” I’d skipped over the “why.”
That experience taught me one of my most valuable early lessons: Details matter—but only when they’re in service of the big picture.
Years later, I was leading a team chartered with a high-stakes, high-visibility initiative: scale one of our core platforms to be more federated, nimble, and configurable for a broad range of clients. We had all the ingredients: funding, vision, and support. But we missed a key constraint—time and dependencies.
The team spent months in refining requirements, UX design and technical explorations. The outcome? A sleek plan that called for a full re-architecture—18 months to first release.
That’s when the alarms started ringing.
I began asking a few simple questions:
“What does success look like post-launch?”
“Which metrics will actually move?”
“How will we migrate clients from the current stack?”
“What’s our rollout plan?”

That’s when the alarms started ringing.
I began asking a few simple questions:
“What does success look like post-launch?”
“Which metrics will actually move?”
“How will we migrate clients from the current stack?”
“What’s our rollout plan?”
“How are we prioritizing the pain points?”
As we unpacked it, one thing became painfully clear: we had chased a bold vision without grounding it in the realities of existing dependencies and customers who needed a practical path forward.
A dependent system was scheduled for deprecation in just six months—meaning our platform needed to support key functionality before then. We didn’t have the luxury of a full 18-month cycle or a big-bang release.
The realization was sobering. We had overinvested in long-term architecture without a viable near-term delivery plan. Valuable time and momentum were lost—all because we skipped a crucial step: zooming in to reality before zooming out on the long-term vision.
👉 Vision without constraints is fantasy. Big-picture clarity keeps bold plans tethered to what’s truly needed—now.

What I Do Differently Now—And encourage others to try
Zooming in and zooming out isn’t something I do once. It is a mental model and way of working I have developed and now setup my mechanisms with the team to help me do the zooming in and out constantly. 
For example, I have regular touch points with my directs and program leads to drive clarity before we dive into execution. Specifically, we align on:
What are we building?
Who is it for?
Why does it matter—what pain are we solving?
How will we measure success?
What’s the fastest, leanest way to start validating our assumptions?
What’s the critical path, where are the unknowns, and how will we track risks? – spending time on these lets me dive deep into the solution design and gives me an opportunity to challenge some of the decisions and/or course correct if needed. 
By grounding the team in these questions early, we create a shared understanding of the end goal, a clear definition of success, and a practical prioritization framework. It ensures we’re solving the right problems, making tradeoffs intentionally, and staying focused on what really moves the needle.
👉 Clarity at the start doesn’t slow you down—it speeds you up and saves you from costly detours later.

🪞Now Your Turn
Build your own zoom-in/zoom-out habit by asking:
What problem am I solving—and who needs it solved now?
Where am I deep in execution but unclear on purpose?
When did I last step back to check alignment with outcomes?
If I asked my team “why are we doing this?”, how many would give the same answer?
Try this: Every Friday, ask yourself and your team one zoom-out question. Build the habit of stepping back—before you dive back in.
I’d love to hear what resonates—or challenges you. Reply to this email and share your story, a lesson you've learned, or even a question that keeps you curious.

Bulletproof Your Career #1: Performance 
Every performance review season, I’ve seen a familiar pattern—over half of my team surprised by how their performance was assessed. Some are shocked by their ratings, but most are just quietly disappointed they weren't rated higher.
In my previous edition on bulletproofing your career, I emphasized performance as the first foundational step. In this edition, let’s go deeper: what does it really mean to perform—and outperform—in your current role?

📖 Real Story: Two Cautionary Tales of Misaligned Expectations
1. The Over-Engineer Who Meant Well
Take GP, an engineer who started with us as an intern. He did reasonably well and earned a return offer as an SDE1. As an intern, he met the bar technically and behaviorally, showing strength in some leadership principles more than others. Overall, he was promising. 
But once he joined full-time, cracks began to show.
His manager noticed he was struggling to deliver on time. Tasks routinely ran late, and he often needed help to finish work. Yet, GP was anything but lazy—he was hardworking, eager, vocal in design meetings, constantly seeking guidance, and regularly burning the midnight oil.
After pairing him with a more experienced engineer, the root cause became clear: GP wasn’t lacking skill—he was over-engineering. In his enthusiasm to impress, he made things more complex than necessary, creating self-imposed scope creep. What he thought was exceeding expectations was actually eroding trust in his ability to deliver.
Eventually, his manager had to put him on a formal performance improvement plan. GP was devastated. In his mind, he had been "going above and beyond." The disconnect between his perception and reality was stark.

2. The Trusted TPM Who Took On Too Much
In another instance, I was conducting a technical assessment of a Senior TPM’s (let’s call him Alex) work for a promotion to Principal. The feedback was glowing—his manager, team, and stakeholders viewed him as a foundational team member. When the SDE responsible for data pipelines and reporting had to leave suddenly due to a personal emergency, Alex stepped up, owned the work, coded the solutions himself, and ensured everything launched on time. He continued to maintain these systems—including monthly time-sensitive tax and compliance reports—long after launch.
Everyone praised his ownership, versatility, and willingness to go beyond his role. Alex was seen as indispensable for the program.
But when I assessed his performance against the Principal TPM bar, something important was missing. While it’s valuable for a TPM to be technically capable, the higher expectation at that level is to establish scalable mechanisms—not become a single point of failure. By personally owning and sustaining critical systems, he hadn’t demonstrated that the program could run without him.
Despite his hard work, I couldn’t support the promotion. I recommended coaching and more time to shift from heroics to system-building. It was a hard pill to swallow—for both him and his manager. But it served as a critical lesson:
The higher you rise, the more your value lies in what you enable—not what you personally execute.

The higher you rise, the more your value lies in what you enable—not what you personally execute.
🔍 The Lesson: Performance Is About Impact, Not Just Effort
Especially early in your career, it’s easy to confuse being busy and working hard with being effective. GP’s story is a powerful reminder that performance isn’t just about working hard—it’s about delivering reliably, at the level expected, and growing from there. Alex’s example is a reminder again that “doing more” doesn’t always translate to higher value, especially as you become more senior.
Here are four simple but essential practices to anchor your performance:
Know the bar. Understand the explicit expectations for your level from job guidelines and, more importantly, from your manager.
Define what “good” looks like. Ask for concrete examples of success in your role.
Seek feedback early and often. Don’t wait for formal reviews. Ask your manager and peers regularly for feedback and listen with the intent to improve, not defend.
Nail the basics before stretching. Meet expectations first. You’ll know when you’re ready to stretch—but don’t rush it, and don’t let comfort make you stagnate either. 
🪞 NOW, REFLECT AND ACT
Don’t wait for your annual review to find out how you're doing. The most successful professionals take ownership year-round—and that starts with a simple but intentional step.

🪞 NOW, REFLECT AND ACT
Don’t wait for your annual review to find out how you're doing. The most successful professionals take ownership year-round—and that starts with a simple but intentional step.
✅ Bring this into your next 1:1—this week if you haven’t already. Use it as a springboard to deepen clarity, close feedback loops, and take control of your performance and career growth.
Here are 5 questions to guide your reflection and discussion:
Do I clearly understand what’s expected of me at my level and in my role?
What are my superpowers—and what are my blind spots?
Do I know what “good” looks like for my role, and am I meeting that bar consistently?
Is there someone I admire in a similar role whom I can learn from or model?
Do I have a trusted mentor or peer who can offer candid, timely coaching?
Remember: Performance isn’t just about effort—it’s about aligned, visible impact.

🙋‍♀️ Let’s Keep the Conversation Going
If this sparked a thought, hit a nerve, or reminded you of your own story—I’d love to hear it.
📩 Feel free to reply by email or drop a comment below:
What resonated with you?
What are you still figuring out?
What’s one step you’re committing to this week?
Performance isn’t a luck or guesswork. It’s a muscle you build—with clarity, feedback, and aligned action.

🛡️ Bulletproof Your Career: Navigating the Unpredictable
The ground is shifting beneath our feet.Layoffs sweep through companies like wildfire. Restructurings reshape entire industries overnight. AI threatens to automate roles we never thought possible. And just when you think your career is on solid footing—the rules change again.
I'm hearing the same anxious questions from professionals at every level: Is there such a thing as job security anymore? How do I keep up with this relentless pace of change? How do I not just survive, but actually thrive?
In this edition, I'm pulling back the curtain on my own experiences with re-orgs and layoffs—what truly helped me stay grounded, and the practical tools I now swear by to bulletproof my career. Think of it as your essential survival guide for navigating change with confidence.
💡 Lesson in a Line
Stay hungry, Stay Curious - adaptability and resilience as your anchors to ride any wave with grace and ease.
📖 Real Story: The Ever-Shifting Terrain
 Over nearly three decades, I've seen the landscape dramatically shift across industries, business models, and leadership styles. I've personally weathered re-orgs, witnessed layoffs up close, and even carried the emotional weight of delivering difficult news.

Over nearly three decades, I've seen the landscape dramatically shift across industries, business models, and leadership styles. I've personally weathered re-orgs, witnessed layoffs up close, and even carried the emotional weight of delivering difficult news.
The first time I had to tell a team member their role was being eliminated, it hit hard. I wasn’t the one who made the decision, but I understood how it was made—performance ratings drew the line. Those below a certain threshold were let go. Clear but felt harsh.
The second time I found myself at the center of a seismic shift was during my time at Dow Jones. The media and publishing industry was undergoing a transformation—print was giving way to digital, and real-time publishing was becoming the norm. Newsrooms were changing overnight, and so were the tools that powered them.
Systems were re-architected from the ground up, and everyone had to learn new ways of doing things. Some struggled to keep up, clinging to the familiar. Others leaned into the change, picked up new skills, and emerged stronger. Dow Jones was the kind of company people stayed at for life, it wasn’t uncommon to see employees start there out of college and retire after decades of service. But even in places like that, loyalty alone isn’t enough. When business priorities shift, so do the rules. If you’re not actively adding value, no amount of tenure will save your seat. It may feel harsh, but it’s not personal, it’s just business.

Most recently in 2022, I was in the middle of another business reprioritization. My entire organization was dissolved. This wasn't about individual performance; it was a pure business decision to shut down a product we'd spent 18 intense months launching. Months of late nights, weekend war-room calls? Gone overnight. It felt like a deep, personal gut punch.
Though my team and I largely avoided layoffs, we were absorbed into a different organization, adrift without clear direction. The roles we inherited were not by choice, and often didn't align with the interests or experience that had drawn us to the original mission. For a group driven by passion and purpose, this unchosen path proved to be profoundly disorienting and demotivating.
Through it all, a clear pattern emerged: The people who thrived had a playbook. A mindset. A toolkit.
Here is what it looked like – a 5-part bulletproof kit
🔧 Your 5-Part Arsenal to Bulletproof Your Career
Performance: Deliver—Then Over-Deliver. Know what excellence looks like in your role and hit it consistently. Go beyond meeting expectations; aim to raise the bar. While this won't always save you from org-wide changes, it keeps you off the "performance" cut list and builds your reputation as an indispensable team member.

Adaptability: Stay Hungry, Stay Curious. Don't confine your learning to your day job. Explore side projects, or hobbies—even if they seem unrelated to your day job. These experiences often spark fresh perspectives, creative thinking, and unexpected connections that feed back into your core work. Staying curious keeps you confident and relevant, no matter what wave hits next. Curiosity doesn’t compete with your career; it compounds it.
Preparedness: Build your safety net before you need it. Career turbulence is inevitable. Panic is optional. A financial buffer gives you breathing room to reflect and make smarter choices. Aim to save 6–12 months of expenses. It’s more than just a fund; it’s peace of mind. Pragmatic is powerful.
Network: Invest in your network now. While we all wish our skills spoke for themselves, the reality is, who you know—and what they say about you—can be just as crucial, if not more so. Especially during times of transition, having a trusted network you can lean on, and who can genuinely vouch for your capabilities, goes far beyond relying on recruiters and cold calls. Beyond job leads, strong connections help you grow, gain perspective, and stay anchored in your journey. Your net worth is truly your network.

Resilience: Your job is not your Identity. With performance, adaptability, preparedness and a trusted network in place, you’ll start to see career setbacks for what they truly are—just chapters, not conclusions. You’ll recover faster, pivot sooner, and bounce back stronger. Resilience isn't just endurance; it's agility with grace.
Remember: Career security isn't about finding the perfect job—it's about becoming the kind of professional who thrives regardless of the weather.
🪞 Now Your Turn
Don’t wait for the next re-org or market shift to ask the hard questions.
Where are you growing—beyond your current role?
Who knows your work and would vouch for you today?
Could you survive a six-month job gap—financially, emotionally, and reputationally?
Pick one area this week to shore up. That’s how you start building a career that thrives—no matter the storm.

🔁 What I’d Do Differently
Looking back, I wish I hadn’t confined my curiosity to just my job. At the height of my career, I gave it everything—110%—and let personal learning and passion projects fall by the wayside, assuming they could wait. I told myself I was “too busy” for side explorations or even casual networking. As a shy introvert, reaching out without a clear reason felt awkward and unnecessary.
But here’s what I’ve learned: career resilience doesn’t come from just being great at your job. It comes from having other sources of energy, confidence, and identity. During re-orgs and surprise changes, I found myself scrambling to react—because I hadn’t built the muscles or relationships to pivot with intent. In hindsight, even small, consistent investments in personal learning and professional connections would’ve given me more options—and more agency especially during re-orgs—to pursue what truly excited me.

I’ve led through hypergrowth, paused to reimagine my path, and made intentional pivots into entrepreneurship, fractional work, and even full-time volunteering in politics

🛡️ Work Life Balance – Myth vs Reality
Jeff Bezos popularized the phrase “work-life harmony,” arguing it’s a better goal than “work-life balance,” which suggests a constant trade-off. In his view, work and life can be seamlessly integrated, each fueling and enriching the other. While this idea is inspiring, it can also set an unrealistic expectation—especially for younger professionals. It may lead to a constant search for the perfect job or life setup, when what’s really needed is greater acceptance of the reality. Work-life harmony is not a static state but a constant juggling of trade-offs. 
In this edition, I’ll share a few real-life examples that shaped my thinking on this topic—and why I believe it’s so important to get clear on what you’re truly aspiring toward. Every desire, every goal we chase, comes with a cost or trade-off. When we’re aware of those trade-offs and make our choices consciously, life begins to feel less discordant and far less stressful.

💡 Lesson in a Line
Set boundaries and learn when and how to stretch them
📖 Real Stories
My first job at Sapient Corp felt like a finishing school—it shaped many of the core values I still carry in both work and life. One of Sapient’s standout features as a new entrant in the consulting space was its bold “Fixed Cost, Fixed Time” delivery model, a stark contrast to the industry’s standard “Time & Materials” approach. That model was my crash course in scope management, estimation, risk planning—and most importantly, learning that even the best-laid plans can fall apart. Always have a Plan B.
Even after I left Sapient, the skills and habits I picked up—especially around estimation and planning—stuck with me. At Dow Jones, I was leading a mission-critical project with a fixed launch date that had already been announced externally.
We wrapped up requirements and UX design by April, leaving just five months to build, test, and ship. I was responsible for the overall end-to-end delivery and was deeply involved in every discussion around scope, technical strategy, resources, risks, and timelines. It became clear fast: even with tight scope and fully loaded teams, the only way to hit the timeline was for the team to work weekends.
My leads and I were frustrated. If leadership had already locked the date, why ask for our input?

My leads and I were frustrated. If leadership had already locked the date, why ask for our input?
Eventually, our director acknowledged the bind we were in and offered a cash bonus to the team for launching on time. That helped, but what really changed the mood was the way the team came together. Despite the rocky setup, we pulled through—and we delivered.
That experience taught me a truth I’ve seen repeated many times since: no matter how thoughtful the culture, how intentional the leadership, or how balanced the environment—there will be moments that demand a stretch. If something is truly important—something the business is counting on—it has to be done on time. Critical opportunities don’t wait. But how leadership shows up in those moments makes all the difference. The way stretch asks are communicated and handled can either build lasting trust—or quietly chip away at it, leading to burnout and eventual attrition.
What I Do Differently Now
Since leaving the services industry, I’ve worked at two very different companies—Dow Jones and Amazon. While their operating styles couldn’t have been more distinct, in both places I was fortunate to be part of teams building products that truly mattered to the business. That meant strong executive backing, but it also came with constant pressure to deliver faster, better, leaner.

Over time, I’ve come to understand that this pressure isn’t a flaw—it’s the cost of working in a thriving, high-growth environment. Today, I’m no longer surprised or frustrated by urgency. As a technology leader, I see it as my role not just to push back on unrealistic demands, but to collaborate with business partners to find a path forward that’s both ambitious and achievable.
I don’t resist time pressure anymore—I work with it. I bring transparency to both sides: helping business stakeholders understand the constraints my team faces, and helping my team understand the “why” behind the urgency. In doing so, we often uncover smarter, more creative ways to meet the goals—without always defaulting to late nights and burnout. When weekend work becomes the unspoken assumption instead of the exception, it erodes trust faster than any missed deadline ever could.

What I Tell Younger Professionals
I often tell my team—and especially younger professionals—not to expect a comfortable, steady work pace all the time. There will be times when you’ll need to stretch. Sometimes it’s because you underestimated the work. Other times, you’ll need to step up for the team. That’s normal. It only becomes a problem when stretching becomes the default, not the exception.
I also remind them: Creating a healthy and sustainable work environment isn’t just the manager’s responsibility. Each team member is responsible for understanding their work, estimating it realistically, planning it thoughtfully, and tracking it diligently. Yes, the manager owns the final commitment on behalf of the team—but that commitment should be based on inputs from everyone. If your estimates are routinely ignored and timelines come top-down without discussion, that’s a red flag to be addressed.
Finally, if you’re never stretched, you’re in the wrong job or too comfortable and stopped growing. If you’re always stretched, you’re in the wrong company.
For anyone trying to create a more sustainable and predictable work life—especially in high-pressure, high-tech environments—here are a few ways to assess and adjust:
Be real and realistic.
Take time to truly understand your company’s business model, its culture, your team’s operating rhythm, and your manager’s working style. How does your manager expect you to plan, report progress, raise risks, and ask for help?

You can’t fix what you don’t see.
Track how you spend your time. What’s actually driving the long hours? Is it a scope problem? Estimation or time management gap? Or a leadership gap?
Zoom out and see the bigger picture.
Is the pressure situational—tied to a specific phase or launch—or is it systemic and recurring? Is this a team-level issue or a broader organizational pattern? Can you speak up and help change it?

🧭 Speak Up or Shut Out: The Career Cost of Staying Quiet
One of the questions I hear most often from young professionals—especially women—is this: How strongly should I advocate for my own career? We’ve all heard “the squeaky wheel gets the grease.” But what if you don’t want to be squeaky—just taken seriously?
If you're delivering solid work but feel like you're being passed over—you’re not alone. This is especially true for women, underrepresented groups, and those new to corporate life who’ve been told, ‘Just work hard and you’ll be rewarded.’ This edition is for you.
This has been one of my own biggest career challenges. I don’t have all the answers, but I’ve learned (sometimes the hard way) how to advocate for myself without losing myself.
In this edition, I’ll share what worked, what didn’t, and the lessons I wish I’d learned sooner.
✨ Lesson in a Line
Being excellent isn’t enough. Being excellent and visible is how you grow. No one will fight for your career harder than you—and if you don’t speak up, no one will.
📚 From the Frontlines: My Real Story

✨ Lesson in a Line
Being excellent isn’t enough. Being excellent and visible is how you grow. No one will fight for your career harder than you—and if you don’t speak up, no one will.
📚 From the Frontlines: My Real Story 
I come from the school of thought that believed in letting the work speak for itself. My focus was always on doing my best, assuming recognition and growth would naturally follow. And early in my career, that seemed true. At Sapient (I was the 70th hire), the company was growing rapidly, and so was I. I had a transparent communication style that kept my manager always in the loop. He could advocate for me even when I wasn’t in the room. Promotions came easily—perhaps too soon, but that’s a story for another day.
Things shifted when I moved to Amazon as a senior leader (Manager of managers). The environment was less intimate, and just doing good work wasn’t enough. I continued to deliver, often going above and beyond, but I rarely brought up career conversations—thinking it would sound self-serving or awkward. I assumed my manager would notice and bring it up when the time was right.

When that didn’t happen, I felt confused and frustrated. My performance ratings were top-tier, yet the growth opportunities weren’t showing up. It wasn’t until I spoke to a few mentors that I realized the gap: I was working hard, but I wasn’t saying I wanted to grow. By not speaking up, I was signaling that I was content where I was. I also reflected on how I treated my team; it was easier to support those who were clear about their growth aspiration vs those who didn’t and ended up disappointed. 
🛠️ What changed: Since then, I’ve made it a habit to talk about my career aspirations every 6 months or so. I share my contributions regularly as always, ask for feedback, and openly discuss what’s next. It has made a real difference—not just in outcomes, but in alignment and mutual clarity. Within couple months of doing this for the first time, my manager did a review of my work summary and acknowledged that I was ready to get to the next level L8-Director and we aligned on a possible timeline and preparatory steps needed to present the case. This level of transparency between us made it easier for him to understand how to support me. 
🔓 What I’ve Learned
Don’t assume your manager knows what you want.
Help them help you. Make your goals clear. Share your wins. Ask for their support. Your current performance builds the credibility necessary to start the conversation and build a plan together for how to move to the next level whatever that may be - lateral or upwards.

At Amazon, we say “leaders are vocally self-critical.”
Many of us also need to learn to be vocally self-advocating.

🪞 Your Reflection: Make It Practical
Ask yourself:
If a stretch role came up today, would your manager advocate for you?
Do they know what you want next—and why?
What’s holding you back from being openly ambitious?
Your work should speak for itself.
But real growth often starts with your voice.

🔁 Looking Back: What I’d Do Differently 
If I could go back, I’d take a longer-term view of my career—not just focus on excelling in the role at hand. My consistent performance earned me a reputation as dependable and respected by peers, managers, and team members alike. But for much of my journey, I never clearly articulated how I wanted to grow professionally. 
Part of that hesitation came from trying to balance a demanding career with being a mom to two young boys. I was cautious about aiming higher, afraid that stretching further might mean compromising at work or at home. Ironically, I was already stretching—ready and willing to take on the next level—but I didn’t turn that into tangible growth. That disconnect left me frustrated, with little to show for all the extra effort.
If I could change one thing, it would be this: to pause, get clear on my aspirations, and have open conversations with my manager about them. Even if at times, I chose to stay in place to focus on family, that clarity—for myself and for my manager—would have built alignment, reduced ambiguity, and fostered greater trust in the journey ahead.

BULLETPROOF YOUR CAREER #2: LIFELONG LEARNING
“The only thing that interferes with my learning is my education.” — Albert Einstein
After raising two kids through school and college, one thing is clear: our education system often squeezes out the very curiosity it should nurture. We’re trained to chase outcomes—grades, degrees, job titles—and somewhere along the way, we stop learning for the joy of it.
But in a world, that’s changing faster than ever, curiosity isn’t optional. It’s essential.
The one skill that never goes out of date is your ability to learn, unlearn, and adapt.

🧭 A Lesson from My Grandfather
One of my earliest lessons on this came when I was around 8. We were gathered at my grandfather’s house for dinner. My grandfather asked me and my older cousins about school. The older ones were discussing what courses to take based on job prospects and salaries. My grandfather listened quietly, then said: “Don’t focus only on jobs and wealth. They can be taken away anytime. Focus on knowledge and skills—those are truly yours forever.”
At the time, I didn’t fully grasp it. But decades later, I see the wisdom clearly. That message—simple, timeless—anchors this edition. It is also the #2 point in my previous edition on Bulletproofing your career.
🔐 Stay Curious. Learn Beyond the Job.
Let me share two stories that bring this to life:
🌱 Tale of a self-taught tinkerer 
One of my first teammates at Sapient was a fresh grad like me and a gifted programmer. In his spare time, he was always building something—carpentry projects, remote-controlled toys for his kids, or home automation devices long before “smart homes” were a thing - all driven by pure curiosity, not grand ambitions.
Even after we moved on, I followed his journey through his blog (another one of his side projects), as he navigated different industries and roles. What stood out was this: his growth wasn’t limited to his day job. It was compounded by what he explored on his own. His constant hands-on exploration made his skills broader and more adaptable and with it came optionality.

🚀 An Engineer’s Pivot to AI
A few years ago, I had a software developer on my team who was curious about AI and machine learning. But there weren’t any immediate opportunities in our org. He didn’t wait. He created a hobby club with other like-minded engineers. They met weekly to explore trends, read research papers, and build side projects. Eventually, they entered our org’s hackathon and demoed an AI-powered solution that caught leadership’s attention—and secured funding. That engineer went on to become a founding member of a new AI team, got promoted, and transitioned into an Applied Scientist role within 18 months.
🔁 What Do These Stories Have in Common?
It wasn’t job titles or timing that made the difference.
It was mindset:
They didn’t confine their curiosity to their job.
They stayed open, self-directed, and eager to explore—without waiting for permission or reward.
💡 What Lifelong Learners Teach Us
Learn for the joy of it.
Reconnect with the curious child in you. Don’t always chase outcomes. Often, what you learn for fun becomes valuable—in unexpected ways.
For example, when I got into gardening, I thought I was just learning to grow plants. But it taught me something deeper—how to nurture with care, observe patiently, and avoid overdoing. These learnings, I realize, are just as applicable to raising kids and leading teams—knowing when to step in, when to step back, and how to create the right conditions for others to thrive.
Let your curiosity wander.

Let your curiosity wander.
Don’t confine your learning into your current field. Your next passion or career shift may be in something you haven’t tried yet.
One of my mentors, PB, was a senior executive who spent weekends learning tailoring and costume design. Today, in retirement, she finds deep fulfillment designing costumes for her local theater group.
Stay focused and agile.
Lifelong learners are agile and adaptable. When roles shift or industries change, their adaptability becomes their superpower. Adaptability gives you agency and resilience.
🛠️ Build a Learning Mindset (Not Just a To-Do List)
I know what you may be thinking: "How do I make time to learn when I'm already stretched thin?"
Here’s the truth: Learning isn’t just another task—it’s a mindset.
It means treating every experience, conversation, or challenge as a chance to grow.
If you're ready to nurture this mindset, here are practical ways to start:
✅ Add personal learning goals to your development plan.
If your company has formal career planning, include your learning goals so your manager can support you. Explore ways to sharpen your skills even outside work. For example, there are ways to sharpen your programming skills by participating in opensource projects and volunteering to fix a bug or build a new feature. 
💵 Use your company’s learning budget.
Many organizations offer training stipends or time. Ask about them and make use of them.
🔁 Rotate into new roles or teams.

💵 Use your company’s learning budget.
Many organizations offer training stipends or time. Ask about them and make use of them.
🔁 Rotate into new roles or teams.
Once you've outgrown your current scope, seek opportunities inside your org.
🙋🏽‍♀️ Volunteer beyond your job description.
Every career pivot I’ve made began with raising my hand for something new.
📚 Read widely.
Even 15 minutes a day adds up. Include fiction and diverse topics—not just work-related ones.
🎨 Make time for hobbies and passion projects.
These are often where your truest learning and joy lie. 
🔍 Now, Over to You

When was the last time you felt wonder, like a child discovering something new?
Are you too comfortable in your job? Growth begins where comfort ends.

🛡️ Bulletproof Your Career #3: Financial Safety Net
This is the third post in my career bulletproofing series and seems most logical and straightforward one, yet the one most people miss acting on. 
When companies restructure or industries shift, your financial cushion determines your choices. Those with a comfortable financial cushion can navigate the uncertainty with more ease, taking the time to deliberate on their next move. Those without feel the pressure to grab the first opportunity, even if it’s not the right fit. But this isn't just about crisis moments. Without intentional planning, lifestyle inflation becomes a golden cage. That bigger house, newer car, or premium lifestyle can quietly transform from comfort into necessity, from freedom into obligation. Before long, you’re working to fund your life instead of letting your money support it.
In this edition, I want to share how my relationship with money was shaped early on and how it’s helped my family and me live with more freedom and intention through different seasons of life.
Respect, not worship

In this edition, I want to share how my relationship with money was shaped early on and how it’s helped my family and me live with more freedom and intention through different seasons of life.
Respect, not worship
My relationship with “money” can be described as “respect”. Growing up in a middle-class or at best upper middle-class family in India, I learned very early on not to take money for granted and to live within my means. My parents tracked every rupee and believed that awareness was the first step to financial clarity. They also taught me never to compare our life to others’, a mindset that has saved me from a great deal of unnecessary pressure and dissatisfaction.

From there to my first job after completing my Master's in the US, I never developed a clear financial strategy beyond those childhood lessons. My husband and I were simply happy we earned enough for what we needed and wanted as a young couple. As we considered buying our first home, my father offered a piece of wisdom that made us think deeper about financial planning: “Try not to over-extend yourself, you still have a long life ahead and having the freedom for one of you to step away from full-time job, if needed is priceless.” I recognize we were fortunate to even consider that kind of option, something many families can’t. Coincidentally, this was the time when a dear friend had just moved into their dream custom home and soon after had their son. Unfortunately, the baby had some health complications and needed multiple surgeries within the first 3 years. What made the situation even more stressful for them was that neither parent could take off from their jobs since they needed both salaries to make the home payments and live their life. This hit home for us. We decided to be more conservative with our financial planning, perhaps one of the defining moments that influenced how we thought about jobs, careers, and money from then on: they should support your life and give you strength, not take over your life.
The Power to Walk Away

The Power to Walk Away
That advice from dad contained another crucial insight: The ability to walk away from a job makes you a better employee. It gives you the confidence to do the right thing, to act with integrity, and to stay true to your values. Without that leverage, work environments that don’t suit you can take a toll on you—not just professionally, but mentally, emotionally, even physically. Having the option to walk away makes you less vulnerable and be more selective about where and with whom you want to invest your time and energy to build your career. 
For example, I was working for Sapient Corp (services firm) when we had our first child. By the time he turned 2, I was also in a senior position and needed to travel extensively as was and still is the norm in the services industry. I was not ready to leave my child with nannies for extended periods of time and so quit the job and took time to find the next one. Thankfully, our conservative approach with our finances gave me the option to leave the job before landing the next one. I was able to step away from my job again just when I was growing well at Dow Jones and this time it was to help the family settle in a new country and also to try out entrepreneurship, freelancing and even satisfy my interest and curiosity in public service.

None of these were easy choices. They didn’t always “make sense” on paper. But they were the right ones for us. These diverse experiences helped me gain a much broader perspective about life and made me develop a deep sense of gratitude for what we already had rather than just be caught up in the corporate rat race. 
People sometimes ask if I regret those breaks. Did they slow down my career or dent our financial portfolio? Possibly. But not meaningfully. What we gained in flexibility was far more valuable. I believe there’s a time for everything, and if those moments had passed without trying, I wouldn't have had another chance.  I’m grateful I didn’t miss those windows.
There's no shortage of financial planning books. I won't replicate their advice. Instead, I want to emphasize one key idea:
Be intentional about designing your lifestyle, and understand what you're giving up to maintain it.
What if creating freedom for one partner to take career breaks meant choosing a $500K home instead of a $900K one? Which tradeoff feels more aligned with your values? That's a deeply personal decision worth reflecting on. What money means to each of us is shaped by our individual journeys. Turning money into a source of strength, not stress, is an individual process that cannot be turned into a one-size-fits-all checklist. It's about getting clear on your values, priorities, and what freedom means to you—finally understanding what you're giving up and for what.
Now your turn

Now your turn
Some questions for you to ponder over as you are working on bullet proofing your career as well as preparing for unexpected things that life can throw at you:
What does money mean to you? Our beliefs around money often stem from childhood, culture, or past experiences. Is it a means to an end? Is it safety, freedom, or identity? There is no right or wrong answer, still worth unpacking.
What are your income sources? Which are fixed and which are flexible? What happens if one goes away? Could your current lifestyle continue, and for how long?
Do you know your monthly run rate? Track expenses for a few months and get clear on your baseline. What portion is driven by your own needs and interests versus keeping up with others? Living well within your means requires thoughtful tradeoffs. What do you value most and refuse to compromise on? Which conveniences are worth paying for? What's optional or driven by “keeping up”?
Do you know what the real cost of your lifestyle is? What are you giving up for keeping it up?
If this resonated with you, I’d love to hear your story—or learn from someone you know who’s walked a similar path. Feel free to share your thoughts, or pass this along to someone who might benefit from or add to the conversation.
Let’s keep this dialogue going.

🛡️ Lean in or lean out?
Can We Really Have It All?
This is one of the questions I get asked the most. And for good reason. The tension between a fulfilling career and a meaningful life is real, relentless, and deeply personal.
I don’t have a silver bullet or a one-size-fits-all answer. But what I do have are real stories—moments of clarity, conflict, and compromise—that shaped how I’ve come to navigate the messy middle. In this edition, I’ll share the choices I’ve made, the trade-offs I’ve wrestled with, and the beliefs I’ve built about what it truly means to “have it all.”
💡 Lesson in a Line
Be real and realistic in your expectations. 
Know what you're chasing—and what it's quietly costing you
📖 Real Stories
Growing up, I remember that on days when school felt especially hard, I couldn’t wait to get home and talk to my mom. Sharing everything with her helped me make sense of what I was feeling and always made things a little better.
But as her health declined during my middle and high school years, that comfort began to disappear. I started coming home to silence—sometimes an empty house, sometimes just the quiet weight of worry. Those years left a mark.

But as her health declined during my middle and high school years, that comfort began to disappear. I started coming home to silence—sometimes an empty house, sometimes just the quiet weight of worry. Those years left a mark. 
When it came time to raise my own children, I was very intentional about being there for them—especially after school or daycare, until bedtime. That one quiet promise I made to myself became the anchor for many of my work and career choices over the years. It wasn’t always easy, but it gave my decisions clarity—and purpose. For example, this meant I said “no” to promotions or roles that needed extensive travel, also meant I stepped away and took a break from corporate job just when I was growing well in my job to help our family with young children settle down in a new country. 
When my boys were young, the juggle was real—and exhausting. My husband and I ran a tightly packed 7-day schedule, balancing work, daycare, school routines, and kids’ activities. Any disruption—whether from work, a school event, or a sick child—threw everything into chaos.

When my boys were young, the juggle was real—and exhausting. My husband and I ran a tightly packed 7-day schedule, balancing work, daycare, school routines, and kids’ activities. Any disruption—whether from work, a school event, or a sick child—threw everything into chaos.
But what truly wore me down wasn’t just unexpected demands. It was the routine ones—like leaders scheduling 5:00 PM meetings, right when I had to leave for daycare pickup. Saying “no” to important meetings again and again wasn’t easy—or well received. That’s when it hit me: my personal constraints didn’t factor into the corporate system. If I chose to stay in it, I had to play by its rules—or accept the trade-offs, like slower growth in certain roles that demanded a lot more of me. 
Once my boys were a little older, I stepped fully into a fast-paced, high-impact role at Amazon. It was demanding, no doubt—but I held firm to one boundary: evenings from 6:00 to 9:30 were sacred family time. After the kids went to bed, I’d log back in and work another 2–3 hours to stay on top of things. It wasn’t easy. I traded personal downtime—my hobbies, my rest—for professional momentum. That was the cost I chose to pay during those years. Still, I’m grateful. The flexibility, the growth, the learning—and yes, even the chaos—shaped me in lasting ways. It was exhausting, sometimes overwhelming, but also incredibly rewarding.

What I Do Differently Now
If I could turn back time and stand at the same crossroads, I would still make the same choices. I knew what mattered most to me, and I stayed true to that.
But if I’m honest, there are a few things I’d do differently. I wish I had trusted myself more and not carried the constant guilt—at home for not doing enough, and at work for drawing boundaries. I wish I hadn’t tried so hard to be everything to everyone.
And I wish I had made space for myself—not just as a parent or a professional, but as a person. Time for hobbies, passion projects, or simply breathing room to explore things that lit me up beyond work and family. That part matters too—and I didn’t see it early enough.
What I’d Tell Younger Professionals
To anyone navigating the juggle of a demanding career and a growing family, here’s what I’ve learned:
Be real—and realistic.
Take the time to understand what your version of a complete life looks like. There are trade-offs to every choice, and ambition always comes with a cost. Be honest with yourself about what you’re willing to give—and what you’re not.
Don’t live by someone else’s script.
It’s easy to internalize others’ expectations or compare your path with someone else’s. But this isn’t a race, and there’s no single finish line. Your life is your own—live it on your terms, not as someone else’s idea of success.
Lean in or lean out—based on what matters to you.
